CDC Communication Study


library(readxl)
library(sjPlot)


data <- read_xlsx("data.xlsx")

H1


t.test(SIDEEFFECTS ~ CONDITION, data = data, alternative = "greater")

    Welch Two Sample t-test

data:  SIDEEFFECTS by CONDITION
t = 0.84343, df = 57.291, p-value = 0.2012
alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group new and group old is greater than 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 -0.3497381        Inf
sample estimates:
mean in group new mean in group old 
         2.750000          2.393939 
model <- lm(SIDEEFFECTS ~ POLORIENTATION * CONDITION, data = data)
tab_model(model)
plot_model(model, type = "int")

H2


t.test(VACCINTENTION ~ CONDITION, data = data, alternative = "less")

    Welch Two Sample t-test

data:  VACCINTENTION by CONDITION
t = -0.20175, df = 53.489, p-value = 0.4204
alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group new and group old is less than 0
95 percent confidence interval:
      -Inf 0.7186095
sample estimates:
mean in group new mean in group old 
         5.750000          5.848485 
model <- lm(VACCINTENTION ~ POLORIENTATION * CONDITION, data = data)
tab_model(model)
plot_model(model, type = "int")


cor.test(data$SIDEEFFECTS, data$VACCINTENTION)


    Pearson's product-moment correlation

# Political orientation: 1 = very liberal ... 7 = very conservative

tab_model(model)
plot_model(model, type = "int")
